### Footnotes

<span id="fn_1182"></span>[195:1183](2010126.htm#fr_1182.md) <span
id="iii.ix.xvii-p2.2"></span>

<span id="iii.ix.xvii-p3"></span> Eusebius in this chapter quotes what
we now know as Justin’s second *Apology,* calling it his first. It is
plain that the two were but one to him. See chap. 18, note 3.

<span id="fn_1183"></span>[195:1184](2010126.htm#fr_1183.md) <span
id="iii.ix.xvii-p4.1"></span>

<span id="iii.ix.xvii-p5"></span> Justin, *Apol.* II. 2.

<span id="fn_1184"></span>[195:1185](2010126.htm#fr_1184.md) <span
id="iii.ix.xvii-p8.1"></span>

<span id="iii.ix.xvii-p9"></span> Our authorities are divided between
<span class="Greek"><span id="iii.ix.xvii-p9.1"></span>ἡ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="iii.ix.xvii-p9.2"></span>μῖν</span> and <span
class="Greek"><span id="iii.ix.xvii-p9.3"></span>ὑ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="iii.ix.xvii-p9.4"></span>μῖν</span>, but I have
followed Heinichen in adopting the former, which has much stronger <span
class="c13"><span id="iii.ix.xvii-p9.5"></span>ms.</span> support, and
which is in itself at least as natural as the latter.

<span id="fn_1185"></span>[195:1186](2010126.htm#fr_1185.md) <span
id="iii.ix.xvii-p12.1"></span>

<span id="iii.ix.xvii-p13"></span> Of this Ptolemæus we know only what
is told us here. Tillemont, Ruinart, and others have fixed the date of
his martyrdom as 166, or thereabouts. But inasmuch as the second Apology
is now commonly regarded as an appendix to, or as a part of, the first,
and was at any rate written during the reign of Antoninus Pius, the
martyrdom of Ptolemæus must have taken place considerably earlier than
the date indicated, in fact in all probability as early as 152 (at about
which time the *Apology* was probably written). We learn from the
opening of the second *Apology* that the martyrdoms which are recorded
in the second chapter, and the account of which Eusebius here quotes,
happened very shortly before the composition of the *Apology* (<span
class="Greek"><span id="iii.ix.xvii-p13.1"></span>χθὲς δὲ καὶ
πρώην</span>, “yesterday and the day before”).

<span id="fn_1186"></span>[195:1187](2010126.htm#fr_1186.md) <span
id="iii.ix.xvii-p13.2"></span>

<span id="iii.ix.xvii-p14"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="iii.ix.xvii-p14.1"></span>᾽</span><span class="Greek"><span
